# Jobs Documentation Rules

## Purpose

Define how the agent creates and maintains persistent job documentation under `.metaproject/jobs/` (default) or `$GDMETAPRO_JOBS_ROOT` (if set).
Jobs are the documentation artifacts produced by the `job-orchestrator` pipeline — they capture the full lifecycle of an orchestrated task (analysis, implementation, review, etc.).

## When To Apply

Apply when:
- `job-orchestrator` creates a new job
- `job-documenter` skill is invoked to create or update job documentation
- User asks about job documentation structure or conventions

## Relationship to `docs/`

`jobs/` and `docs/` are **separate systems**:
- `docs/` — general project documentation (requirements, plans, reports, analysis). Managed by `documentation-management.mdc`.
- `jobs/` — orchestrator pipeline artifacts. Each job is a self-contained folder documenting one orchestrated task end-to-end.

Standalone skill invocations (e.g. `feature-analyzer` without orchestrator) continue to use `docs/analysis/`.
Only orchestrator-driven work produces output in `jobs/`.

## Root Location

```
.metaproject/jobs/          # default — project-local jobs directory
$GDMETAPRO_JOBS_ROOT            # override — if environment variable is set
```

## JOBS_ROOT Resolution

The jobs root is resolved in this priority order:

1. **`JOBS_ROOT` passed explicitly** by the orchestrator in the sub-agent dispatch prompt
2. **`GDMETAPRO_JOBS_ROOT` environment variable** (if set in the shell)
3. **`.metaproject/jobs/`** — default, relative to the project being worked on

```bash
JOBS_ROOT="${GDMETAPRO_JOBS_ROOT:-.metaproject/jobs}"
```

`PROJECT_DIR` is always known by Phase 0.2 of the orchestrator. Sub-agents (job-documenter, context-collector, task-implementer, etc.) **never resolve JOBS_ROOT themselves** — they receive it explicitly from the orchestrator in the dispatch prompt.

## Job Folder Naming

- **Format:** `<context-slug>` — kebab-case, lowercase, alphanumeric + hyphens only.
- **Auto-generated** by orchestrator from context, then confirmed with user.
- **Naming patterns:**

| Intent | Example Name |
|--------|-------------|
| Issue implementation | `issue-4141--mobx-sync-fix` |
| Issue analysis only | `analysis--issue-4141` |
| Feature analysis | `analysis--pipeline-variables` |
| Code review | `review--pr-4144` |
| Custom task | `task--refactor-store-layer` |

- Prefix indicates intent type: `issue-`, `analysis--`, `review--`, `task--`.
- Double hyphen `--` separates the prefix from the descriptive slug.
- Keep names concise but descriptive (max ~60 characters).

## Required Structure

Every job folder MUST contain at minimum:

```
.metaproject/jobs/<job-name>/
  README.md          # Job index — always present, always up-to-date
  man/               # Human-readable documents
  ai/                # AI-optimized documents (structured markdown, Gherkin, etc.)
  results/           # task-implementer JSON result files (created automatically)
    task-1.json      # Full result for task-1 (written by task-implementer Phase 6)
    task-2.json      # Full result for task-2
    ...
```

> **`results/` folder:** Created by `task-implementer` during Phase 6 (one file per task). The orchestrator and wave-executor never receive full task results inline — they read these files only when a task reports `DONE_WITH_CONCERNS` or `BLOCKED`. This keeps the orchestrator context bounded.

## README.md Format

The README is the entry point for both humans and AI agents. It MUST contain:

```markdown
# Job: <Job Title>

## Status
<!-- One of: in-progress | completed | aborted | paused -->
**Status:** in-progress
**Created:** <ISO 8601 timestamp>
**Updated:** <ISO 8601 timestamp>

## Description
<1-3 sentences describing what this job does>

## Context
| Key | Value |
|-----|-------|
| Intent | <analyze / implement / review / custom> |
| Source | <issue URL, PR URL, or description> |
| Project | <project directory path> |
| Branch | <feature branch name, if any> |
| Base Branch | <base branch> |

## Plan
<!-- Ordered list of planned steps with status -->
1. [x] Analyze issue (issue-analyzer)
2. [ ] Prepare feature branch
3. [ ] Implement tasks (task-implementer)
4. [ ] Review (code-ai-review, code-boss-review, code-style-review)
5. [ ] Fix review findings
6. [ ] Final checks
7. [ ] Generate report

## Agents Used
| Agent | Phase | Status |
|-------|-------|--------|
| issue-analyzer | Analysis | completed |
| task-implementer | Implementation | in-progress |
| code-ai-review | Review | pending |

## Documents

### Human-Readable (`man/`)
| File | Description | Status |
|------|-------------|--------|
| [analysis.md](man/analysis.md) | Issue decomposition and analysis | final |
| [plan.md](man/plan.md) | Implementation plan | final |
| [report.md](man/report.md) | Implementation report | draft |

### AI-Optimized (`ai/`)
| File | Description | Status |
|------|-------------|--------|
| [analysis.md](ai/analysis.md) | Structured analysis for sub-agents | final |
| [tasks.feature](ai/tasks.feature) | Gherkin scenarios for implementation | final |

## Problems & Notes
<!-- Any issues encountered, decisions made, blockers -->
- None so far
```

## Document Types

Standard document names (used in both `man/` and `ai/`):

| Name | Purpose | Typical Content |
|------|---------|----------------|
| `analysis.md` | Issue/feature decomposition | Analysis results, affected areas, dependencies |
| `plan.md` | Execution plan | Ordered steps, agents to use, expected outcomes |
| `report.md` | Implementation report | What was done, files changed, commits made |
| `review.md` | Review findings | Reviewer results, severity, file:line references |
| `context.md` | Unified context document | Collected local/external context, library docs, best practices |
| `final-report.md` | Aggregated final report | Complete summary of entire job |
| `improvements.md` | Suggested improvements | Post-job improvement suggestions |
| `requirements.md` | Requirements gathered | Requirements extracted during analysis |
| `error-log.md` | Error documentation | Errors encountered during job execution |
| `tasks.feature` | Gherkin scenarios (ai/ only) | Atomic task definitions for sub-agents |
| `review-findings.md` | Structured review data (ai/ only) | Machine-parseable review results |

Custom names are allowed but MUST follow kebab-case convention.

## Document Metadata

Every document (in both `man/` and `ai/`) MUST end with a metadata block:

```markdown

---

<!-- Document Metadata -->
| Key | Value |
|-----|-------|
| Created | 2026-02-20T14:30:00Z |
| Agent | issue-analyzer |
| Task | Analyze issue #4141 |
| Job | issue-4141--mobx-sync-fix |
| Version | 1.0 |
| Status | final |
```

**Status values:** `draft` | `final` | `updated` | `error`

**Version:** Starts at `1.0`. Incremented when document is updated (e.g. after review-fix loop: `1.0` → `1.1`).

## `man/` vs `ai/` Content Guidelines

### `man/` — Human-Readable
- Written in clear, narrative markdown
- Includes context and explanations
- Uses headings, bullet points, tables for readability
- Code snippets are illustrative, not exhaustive
- Suitable for reading by developers, leads, PMs

### `ai/` — AI-Optimized
- Structured for machine parsing
- Uses consistent formats: Gherkin features, structured tables, JSON-like blocks
- Includes full file paths, line numbers, exact identifiers
- Minimal prose — data-dense
- Suitable for feeding into sub-agents as context

## Prohibited

- Creating a job folder without `README.md`
- Writing documents outside `.metaproject/jobs/<job-name>/` during a job
- Mixing `man/` and `ai/` content in the same file
- Using non-kebab-case file names
- Leaving README.md out of sync with actual documents in the folder
- Deleting or overwriting job folders without user confirmation
- Creating job documentation for standalone skill invocations (use `docs/` instead)

## Lifecycle

1. **Init** — Orchestrator determines job name, calls documenter to create folder + README + plan
2. **Active** — After each sub-agent completes, orchestrator sends results to documenter. Documents are added to `man/` and `ai/`. README is updated.
3. **Finalize** — Orchestrator calls documenter to write final report, update README status to `completed`, add completion timestamp.
4. **Archived** — Job folder remains in `jobs/` indefinitely. Old jobs are NOT auto-deleted.
